This section describes the economic impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic on the Nepali tourism workforce.

Tourism is a big, important industry in Nepal. In 2019, the sector created **1.03 million jobs**, and employed almost 7% of the Nepali workforce {% sidenote '1' 'World Travel and Tourism Council (2020), Travel & Tourism Economic Impact. Country report available on request.' %}. What makes the industry even more important, is the fact that it **contributes to nearly a third of Nepal's earnings from exports.** 

As part of C2M2 Kathmandu, we conducted a survey in collaboration with 107 tourism professionals from Kathmandu to understand the toll COVID-19 has taken on people who depend on tourism for their livelihoods. 





### still looking
Of the 107 people surveyed, nearly 80% of the population report that they are currently out of work. While some of them have left entirely, most of them are currently looking for opportunities to re-engage themselves in the tourism sector.

{% maincolumn 'assets/img/charts/workers_2_engaged_w_tourism.png' 'While this is unfortunate, results shown on the graph are somewhat expected, as most of our respondents earn their livings working as guides and porters.  See survey demographics.' %}


### Severe financial impacts
A very small fraction of our respondents were able to retain their jobs from before the pandemic. Salary cuts were a common occurence. 

{% maincolumn 'assets/img/charts/workers_employment.png' 'The option "Reduced to almost zero" was added on the insistence of participants from our pilot testing exercise. They felt that none of the other options were representative of the situation on the ground.' %}
 

With tourist numbers reduced to near-zero for months, professionals in the travel and adventure space seem to be the hardest hit. More than 95% of our respondents report income losses of more than 50% compared to 2019.


{% maincolumn 'assets/img/charts/workers_4_income_change.png' 'The option "Reduced to almost zero" was added on the insistence of participants from our pilot testing exercise. They felt that none of the other options were representative of the situation on the ground.' %}
 
### AN INFORMAL INDUSTRY
